column18: I enjoyed how it didn't automatically generate the code that I needed to use, I enjoyed that I felt like I was leading the interaction with the tool rather than being fully dependent on it. This was my first time coding with copilot assistance and it was a fun experience to learn how it works.

column2: Beginner – I can write a correct implementation for a simple function
column18: I have never used Copilot before but really enjoyed collaborating with it. I haven't analyzed data using Python for a couple months now so all of the functions I would usually use slipped my mind. Collaborating with Copilot felt like I was googling what I wanted to do except instead of going through several stack overflow links that Google would show me, the code just appeared inline saving me time and keeping my flow of coding. Looking forward to using Copilot more in the future now!

column18: Copilot increases the productivity of a developer by a great extent, and I can see that we are not far away from reaching to a point where the dev can just give a spec and we'll have the code. However, I worry that bugs can sneak-in and go unnoticed, especially in weakly-dynamically typed languages. Use of copilot with statically and strongly typed languages seems best to me and with automatic test case generation, copilot is going to take software development into a new maturity level. It was great to be a part of this study and I am happy to contribute further as well.

column18: I think my answers above would have changed significantly if I had prior experience using Copilot.  Since this was my first interaction with Copilot, I didn't have a good sense for what it was capable of and not capable of, so I spent some time doing things that more experienced Copilot users would not have tried.  In this short user-study I found Copilot somewhat distracting, but with some more experience I think it would provide benefit in some instances, and I would know when to switch towards leveraging it.

column2: Advanced – I can design and implement a complex system architecture
column18: My main concern with Copilot is whether it is teaching me to do things the wrong (or old) way (e.g. showing me a Python 3.6 way instead of a Python 3.10 way and so on).  It would be cool if Copilot could estimate how confident it is about a given suggestion with some sort of chain of evidence that this is the current best way of doing things that I could double check myself with some online web searches and so on.
